  "prompt": "How can you determine the molecular mass of ammonium?",
  "response": "To determine the molecular mass of ammonium (NH4+), we need to add up the atomic masses of all the atoms in the molecule. \n\nAmmonium is composed of one nitrogen atom and four hydrogen atoms. The atomic mass of nitrogen is approximately 14.01 g/mol, and the atomic mass of hydrogen is approximately 1.01 g/mol. \n\nSo, the molecular mass of ammonium can be calculated as follows: \n\n1 nitrogen atom x 14.01 g/mol = 14.01 g/mol\n4 hydrogen atoms x 1.01 g/mol = 4.04 g/mol\n\nAdding these values together gives us the molecular mass of ammonium:\n\n14.01 g/mol + 4.04 g/mol = 18.05 g/mol\n\nTherefore, the molecular mass of ammonium (NH4+) is approximately 18.05 g/mol.",
